<h2>Why the ring is better for sleep</h2>
<img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1559757148-5c350d0d3c56?w=800&q=80" alt="Accurate sleep tracking data" style="width:100%;border-radius:10px;aspect-ratio:16/9;object-fit:cover;margin-bottom:20px;" loading="lazy"/>
<p>Physics matters here. The finger has more superficial arteries than the wrist, so optical sensors read heart rate and HRV with greater accuracy. Also, without a screen or strap, it's much more comfortable to sleep with.</p>
<p>In comparative tests, the Oura Ring correctly detects sleep stages 15-20% more than Apple Watch or Garmin. For someone wanting to improve their sleep, that difference is significant.</p>
<h2>Why the smartwatch is better for sports</h2>
<p>If you run, cycle or do any outdoor sport, integrated GPS in a smartwatch is irreplaceable. The ring has no GPS. For training metrics like pace, distance and route map, you need a smartwatch or sports watch.</p>
<p>Smartwatches also win on exercise metric variety: they automatically detect more activity types, measure VO2 max more accurately during intense exercise, and some monitor ECG.</p>
<h2>What if I want both?</h2>
<p>It's the combination used by many serious athletes: a ring for sleep and recovery, a GPS smartwatch or sports watch for workouts. They don't duplicate — they complement each other.</p>
